         <abstract>
            <p>In this paper we derive a relation concerning the speed of convergence of the nearest integer and regular continued fractions. If $A_n/B_n, p_k/q_k$ denote the convergents of the nearest integer and regular continued fractions of an irrational number $\alpha$, then for all $n$ there is a $k(n)$ such that $A_n/B_n = p_{k(n)}/q_{k(n)}$. It is shown that $$\operatornamewithlimits{\lim}_{n \rightarrow \infty} \frac{n}{k(n)} = \frac{\log \big(\frac{1 + \surd \overline 5}{2}\big)}{\log 2}$$ for almost all $\alpha$. This problem is reduced to a special case of a general result concerning the frequency of partial quotients in the regular continued fraction (Theorem 2).</p>
          </abstract>
